"Gassó N., Sol D., Pino J., Dana E.D., Lloret F., Sanz-Elorza M., Sobrino E., Vilà M.","Exploring species attributes and site characteristics to assess plant invasions in Spain",2009,"Diversity and Distributions","15","1",,"50","58",,,10.1111/j.1472-4642.2008.00501.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-57349152570&partnerID=40&md5=4231c998cd05d2dd0be30f0426ccc4d8","CREAF (Centre for Ecological Research and Forestry Applications), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, E-08193 Bellaterra, Catalonia, Spain; EGMASA (Empresa de Gestión Medioambiental), E-41092 Sevilla, Spain; Gerencia Territorial del Catastro, E-40001 Segovia, Spain; Departamento de Ingeniería, Producción Y Economía Agraria, Escuela Técnica Superior de Ingeniería Agraria, Universidad de La Laguna, E-38200 La Laguna, Spain; EDB-CSIC (Estacion Biologica de Donana, Centro Superior de Investigaciones Cientificas), E-41013 Sevilla, Spain; CREAF (Centre for Ecological Research and Forestry Applications), Edifici C, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, E-08193 Bellaterra, Catalonia, Spain","Gassó, N., CREAF (Centre for Ecological Research and Forestry Applications), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, E-08193 Bellaterra, Catalonia, Spain, CREAF (Centre for Ecological Research and Forestry Applications), Edifici C, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, E-08193 Bellaterra, Catalonia, Spain; Sol, D., CREAF (Centre for Ecological Research and Forestry Applications), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, E-08193 Bellaterra, Catalonia, Spain; Pino, J., CREAF (Centre for Ecological Research and Forestry Applications), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, E-08193 Bellaterra, Catalonia, Spain; Dana, E.D., EGMASA (Empresa de Gestión Medioambiental), E-41092 Sevilla, Spain; Lloret, F., CREAF (Centre for Ecological Research and Forestry Applications), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, E-08193 Bellaterra, Catalonia, Spain; Sanz-Elorza, M., Gerencia Territorial del Catastro, E-40001 Segovia, Spain; Sobrino, E., Departamento de Ingeniería, Producción Y Economía Agraria, Escuela Técnica Superior de Ingeniería Agraria, Universidad de La Laguna, E-38200 La Laguna, Spain; Vilà, M., EDB-CSIC (Estacion Biologica de Donana, Centro Superior de Investigaciones Cientificas), E-41013 Sevilla, Spain","Aim: Biological invasions are a major component of global change with increasing effects on natural ecosystems and human societies. Here, we aim to assess the relationship between plant invader species attributes and the extent of their distribution range size, at the same time that we assess the association between environmental factors and plant invader species richness. Location: Spain, Mediterranean region. Methods: From the species perspective, we calculated the distribution range size of the 106 vascular plant invaders listed in a recently published atlas of alien plant species in Spain. Range size was used as an estimation of the degree of invasion success of the species. To model variation in range size between species as a function of a set of species attributes, we adopted the framework of the generalized linear mixed models because they allow the incorporation of taxonomic categories as nested random factors to control for phylogenetic relationships. From the invaded site perspective, we determined invader plant species richness as the number of species for each 10 × 10 km Universal Transverse Mercator (UTM) grid. For each grid cell, we estimated variables concerning landscape, topography, climate and human settlement. Then, we performed a generalized linear mixed model incorporating a defined spatial correlation structure to assess the relationship between plant invader richness and the environmental predictors. Results: From the species perspective, wind dispersal and minimum residence time appeared to favour invasion success. From the invaded site perspective, we identified high anthropogenic disturbance, low altitude, short distance to the coastline and dry, hot weather as the main correlates to UTM grid cell invader richness. Main conclusions: According to these results, an increasing importance of man-modified ecosystems and global warming in the Mediterranean region should facilitate the expansion of plant invaders, especially wind-dispersed species, leading to the accumulation of invasive species in some sites (i.e. invasion hot spots). © 2008 The Authors.","Biological invasions; Climate; Life-history traits; Man-induced disturbance; Mediterranean region; Residence time; Seed dispersal; Spatial autocorrelation; Taxonomic bias","autocorrelation; biological invasion; ecological modeling; human settlement; life history trait; Mediterranean environment; phylogenetics; range size; residence time; seed dispersal; species richness; taxonomy; vascular plant; Eurasia; Europe; Southern Europe; Spain; Tracheophyta",,,,,,"Anselin, L., (1988) Spatial Econometrics: Methods and Models., , Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht, The Netherlands; Anselin, L., Bera, A.K., Spatial dependence in linear regression models with an introduction to spatial econometrics (1998) Handbook of Applied Economic Statistics, pp. 237-289. , (ed. by. Ullah A. Giles D.E.A. pp. Marcel Dekker, New York; Atkinson, I.A.E., Cameron, E.K., Human influence on the terrestrial biota and biotic communities of New Zealand (1993) Trends in Ecology and Evolution, 8, pp. 447-451; Becker, T., Dietz, H., Billeter, R., Buschmann, H., Edwards, P.J., Altitudinal Distribution of alien plant species in the Swiss Alps (2005) Prespectives in Plant Ecology, Evolution and Systematics, 8, pp. 173-183; Bjørnstad, O.N., (2004) R Package Version 1.0-6, , http://onb.ent.psu.edu/onb1/R; Blackburn, T.M., Duncan, R.P., Determinants of establishment success in introduced birds (2001) Nature, 414, pp. 195-197; Bolós, O., Vigo, J., Masalles, R.M., Ninot, J.M., (1993) Flora Manual Dels Països Catalans., , Editorial Pòrtic, Barcelona, Spain; Brändle, M., Stadler, J., Klotz, S., Brandl, R., Distributional range size